Red Wine Exploration

Danielle Taneyo

Monday, October 31, 2016

========================================================

This is my exploration of the red wine data. To assess the quality of a wine, it can be use sensorial analysis and physicochemical analysis. In this project I will explore the data from Cortez et al., 2009.

Load the packages and read the data

New function

describe <- function(df, col){
v <- df[, col]
sumry <- summary(v)
ns <- names(sumry)
ns <- c(ns, 'std')
out <- c(sumry, sd(v))
names(out) <- ns
round(out, digit = 3)
}

As the first view, he have some variables with a high range like residual.sugar, total.sulfur.dioxide, citric.acid, free.sulfur.dioxide and volatile.acidity. The quality variable is the dependent or response variable, it’s a sensorial score between 0 and 10, 0 is worst and 10 best.In this data the score is between 3 and 8 with an average of 5.6. I will try to respond to 2 questions here:
1. Which properties can influence the wine quality?
2. Is there some relation between these properties?

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

This data consist of 1599 red wines with 11 variables of their chemical properties. The 11 variables:

  1. fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g/dm^3)
  2. volatile acidity (acetic acid - g/dm^3)
  3. citric acid (g/dm^3)
  4. residual sugar (g/dm^3)
  5. chlorides (sodium chloride - g/dm^3
  6. free sulfur dioxide (mg/dm^3)
  7. total sulfur dioxide (mg/dm^3)
  8. density (g/cm^3)
  9. pH
  10. sulphates (potassium sulphate - g/dm3)
  11. alcohol (% by volume)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest is the sulphate content, pH, alcohol, total sulfur dioxide.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Volatile acidity, citric acid and residual sugar are interesting features to support the analysis as they are also use as indicators in the fermentation process of wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I create a new variable to convert the quality in ordinal factor.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Sulphates and residual sugar distributions were right-skewed so I log transformed them. Transforming the data I saw that the peak was around 0.6 for sulphates and 2.2 for residual sugar.
For others variable I adjust the binwidth and the scale to have a better view of small values.

The pH determines the acidity/basicity of a wine, low pH gives acidity and high gives basicity, usually the wine’s pH is around 3-4. Also the pH is a barrier for microbial growth, so having a low pH protect the wine from degradation.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot shows that most of the wine were of medium quality with an average amount of sulphates around 0.65. Most wines of high quality has a sulphate average of 0.76 whereas the low quality has an average around 0.56. So a good wine should have more sulphates to preserve their properties.

Plot Two

Description Two

The alcohol percent is high in high quality wines. The low and medium wines quality have the same median.

Plot Three

Description Three

The pH decreases as the citric acid increases and this relationship is more strong in high quality wines. It’s more likely to found high quality wine with low pH and high citric acid. Medium and high a range from 0 to 0.8 of citric acid.

Reflection

I used univariate, bivariate and multivariate analysis to found the most important parameters defining the wine quality. Using the bivariate analysis some trends were very clear. Red wine quality is mostly influenced by the sulphate content, pH, alcohol, volatile acidity and total.sulfur.dioxide. It was difficult to find the better way of visualization of each features because some distribution were skewed. I struggled understanding why the correlation of the citric acid with pH is so different among the different quality, looking at the scatterplot separetly I saw that their distribution are different and also there are few wine of low quality.
This analysis can be useful to verify the authenticity and quality of red wine, but there are some limitations of the data. First, the observations is unbalanced, we have few observations of low and high quality wine, this can give some bias on the analysis. Finally it could be also good to have an idea of the law limits of each parameters in that country in order to remove it from the analysis. In the future this data could be use for machine learning, to classify and predict the wine quality.
